  "answer": "Both texts are in the corpus and yield clear operative claims, but with very different frameworks.\n\n**Bṛhaspati Smṛti** (`unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070`, ch. 1): Bṛhaspati introduces *lekhya* (the document) as one of three canonical kinds of human proof in the vyavahara (legal procedure) scheme — 'Witnesses, documents, and possession are remembered as the three kinds of human proof; divine proof is of nine kinds' (Brh_1,4.7, p-510297). The operative rationale for the lekhya category appears at Brh_1,6.2 (p-579a7b): 'Because confusion arises over time even in matters of debt and the like, the Creator of old created letters, set down on a leaf.' Writing was invented specifically to overcome the fallibility of memory and oral testimony. The relative-strength rule follows directly: 'When a mortgage, sale, or gift is made by means of witnesses and a document, and bound by a single transaction, the document there is the prevailing one' (Brh_1,10.46, p-3f1bb6). And Brh_1,10.47 (p-3c8fd3) adds, citing Kātyāyana: 'what is written with particulars is stronger.' So Bṛhaspati's operative claim is that documents are superior to oral witness testimony in commercial/property disputes — lekhya explicitly trumps sākṣin when both exist. That said, documents can be forged and must survive scrutiny: 'By truthfulness, it is a proof; by a flaw, it is an invalidation' (Brh_1,6.34).\n\n**Charles Comte, Traité de Législation** (`charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2`, ch. 11): Comte's operative claim is epistemic rather than procedural. His chapter 11 argues that writing is a *description* of legal/social facts, not the facts themselves: 'The writing by means of which one describes the material fact that a law produces is but the expression of the thought of a certain number of men; it is not a primary cause, it is an effect and a means' (p-b919f1). Applied to civil records — births, deaths, sales, donations — Comte says: 'these descriptions serve to record the events that have happened, and to preserve their memory; but, if one ceased to describe these events, or to record them as they occur, would they exist any less? … The lack of description of the events of civil life would doubtless entail grave inconveniences; but these events would happen nonetheless' (p-23c19d). The error, Comte insists, is 'taking a description for a law, the written affirmation of a certain order of facts for the very existence of those facts.' Writing is evidence of social reality, not constitutive of it. He does not rank writing explicitly against oral testimony, but his framework implies both are just descriptions of the underlying social fact — and that all nations had unwritten (i.e., oral/customary) laws before writing spread.\n\n**On relative reliability vs. oral testimony:** The traditions diverge sharply. Bṛhaspati clearly positions lekhya as more reliable than witness testimony in disputes over property and debt (documents prevail, and were invented precisely because memory fails over time). Comte does not make a direct comparison of writing versus oral testimony's reliability; his concern is that writing is mistaken for legal substance rather than evidence. If anything, Comte's philosophical stance is that writing is no more or less authoritative than any other description of an underlying social reality — which subtly deflates writing's epistemic privilege without elevating oral testimony.",
